            ],
            "abstractNote": "I examined relationships between tongue length of orchid bees (Apidae: Euglossini) and nectar spur length of their ﬂowers in the genera Calathea, Costus, and Dimerocostus using phylogenetically independent contrasts. Long-tubed ﬂowers have specialized on one or several species of long-tongued euglossine bees, but longtongued bees have not specialized on long-tubed ﬂowers. Whereas long tongues may have evolved to provide access to a wider variety of nectar resources, long nectar spurs may be a mechanism for ﬂowers to conserve nectar resources while remaining attractive to traplining bee visitors.",
