            "abstractNote": "The state of Nayarit is located in western Mexico, a key region in the biogeographic understanding of the Mexican mammal fauna. Available literature was reviewed in regard to both, the terrestrial and the marine mammals, known from state of Nayarit, Mexico. Thirteen orders, 30 families, 88 genera, and 143 species are currently known for the state, with 32 endemic species for the country and 6 at state level. Most diverse orders are Chiroptera (61 species), Rodentia (33), Cetacea (20), and Carnivora (17); with 31 taxa described based on specimens collected at the state. It is noteworthy that bat species almost duplicate the number of rodent species, while both at international and national level, rodents are the most abundant. Regarding the species distribution, most of them have Mesoamerican affinities (53), rather than Nearctic (41) or Neotropical (29). Forty-one species are listed within either national or international conservation lists, including the 21 marine species.",
